{{Infobox choir | name = Orfeón Donostiarra | image = Actuación del Orfeón Donostiarra (1 de 2) - Fondo Car-Kutxa Fototeka.jpg | caption = In concert in 1941 | origin = | founder = Miguel Oñate | headquarters = [[San Sebastián]], [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]], Spain | founding = {{start date|1897}} | genre = Mixed concert choir | members = | chief conductor = José Antonio Sáinz | affiliation = | awards = | website = {{url|http://www.orfeondonostiarra.org}} }} The '''Orfeón Donostiarra''' is a concert choir based in [[San Sebastián]], [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]], Spain.<ref>{{cite web | author=| title=Orfeon Donostiarra/Donostiako Orfeoia| url=http://www.onct.mairie-toulouse.fr/en/concerts/players/download/Orfeon-Donostiarra-bio.rtf| publisher= | date=| accessdate=15 August 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>
==History== The choir was formed in 1897 in [[San Sebastián]]. The first music directors were Miguel Oñate, Luzuriaga and Esnaola. In June 1906 the group was awarded the Gran Prix of Paris. The next music director was Juan Gorostidi, who served until his death 1968, when Antxón Ayestarán became the next conductor. Since 1986 the choir is conducted by its presend music director José Antonio Sáinz.<ref>{{cite web | author=| title=Orfeón Donostiarra| url=http://fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/en/awards/1984/orfeon-donostiarra-1/text/| publisher=Premios Príncipe de Asturias | date=| accessdate=15 August 2009}}</ref>
At the heart of the Chorus's repertoire are the most important ''a capella'' works from the 18th century to our time, as well as the great nineteenth and twentieth century large scale orchestral choral works. The choir has been invited to perform with orchestras such as the [[Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra]], the [[English Chamber Orchestra]], the [[Czech Philharmonic]], the [[Dresden Philharmonic]], the [[Royal Liverpool Philharmonic]], the [[Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin]], [[Madrid Symphony Orchestra]], [[Israel Chamber Orchestra]], [[Lucerne Festival Orchestra]], [[Spanish National Orchestra]], [[Residentie Orchestra]], [[Bilbao Symphony Orchestra]], [[West-Eastern Divan (orchestra)|West-Eastern Divan]], [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]], and [[Russian National Orchestra]].
Conductors have included [[Claudio Abbado]],<ref>{{cite web | author=| title=Abbado 'afinó' con excelencia al Orfeón Donostiarra| url=http://www.elmundo.es/papel/2003/08/21/uve/1461403.html| publisher=El Mundo | date=| accessdate=15 August 2009}}</ref> [[Ataúlfo Argenta]], [[Daniel Barenboim]], [[Kurt Masur]], [[Rafael Frühbeck de Burgos]], [[Jesús López-Cobos]], [[Peter Maag]], [[Charles Mackerras]], [[Igor Markevitch]], [[Lorin Maazel]], [[Zubin Mehta]], [[Riccardo Muti]], [[Seiji Ozawa]], [[Esa-Pekka Salonen]] and [[Leopold Stokowski]], among others.<ref>{{cite web | author=| title=Orfeon Donostiarra/Donostiako Orfeoia| url=http://www.onct.mairie-toulouse.fr/en/concerts/players/download/Orfeon-Donostiarra-bio.rtf| publisher= | date=| accessdate=15 August 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=| title=Who are we| url=http://www.orfeondonostiarra.org/ingles/quienes.php| publisher= | date=| accessdate=15 August 2009}}</ref>
== Recordings == The Orfeón Donostiarra has recorded over 120 CDs, including CDs for [[EMI]], [[RTVE|RTVE Música]] and [[Deutsche Grammophon]].
The performance of [[Symphony No. 2 (Mahler)|Mahler's Second Symphony]] with the [[Lucerne Festival Orchestra]] and [[Claudio Abbado]] has been released on DVD<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www2.deutschegrammophon.com/special/?ID=abbado-mahler2 | title=Claudio Abbado - Gustav Mahler: Symphony No. 2 | publisher=''Deutsche Grammophon'' | author=| date=| accessdate=2009-08-28}}</ref> and YouTube (per EuroArts).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4MPuoOj5TIw | title=Claudio Abbado - Gustav Mahler: Symphony No. 2 | publisher=EuroArtsChannel/YouTube | date=| accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref>
